Wait, `List.map` is not the same as `List.filter`. `List.map f l` applies `f` to each element of `l`. `List.filter p l` keeps elements of `l` where `p` is true.

So `List.map Request.id state.removed` is a list of `id`s of the removed requests.
If `r` is a request in `state.removed`, then `r`'s `id` is in `List.map Request.id state.removed`.

The new `state`'s `removed` list is `List.filter (fun r => r ≠ rId) state.removed`.
So the new `List.map` is `List.map Request.id (List.filter (fun r => r ≠ rId) state.removed)`.

If `id ∈ List.map Request.id state.removed`, then `id` is an `id` of a removed request.
If `id ≠ rId`, then `id` is in the new `List.map`.
If `id = rId`, then `id` is not in the new `List.map`.

